    <h1 style="color: rgb(0, 119, 255);">EXPLORING EARTH SCIENCE WITH NASA: A LOOK AT OUR HOME</h1>
     <!--This is a picture of our home(The Earth) a pale blue dot in the solar system-->
    <img src="images/Grober-EarthTermsandConditions.webp" alt="">
    <P>Welcome to NASA's Earth Science Program, where we study our home planet from space to better understand its interconnected systems, dynamics, and changes over time. From monitoring climate patterns to tracking natural disasters and studying the effects of human activity, NASA's Earth Science research plays a vital role in advancing our understanding of Earth and informing decisions to protect our planet and safeguard our future.</p>
        <h2 style="color: rgb(0, 119, 255);">Mission Overview:</h2>
        <p>NASA's Earth Science Program is dedicated to advancing our knowledge of Earth as a dynamic, complex system and addressing critical challenges facing our planet and society. Our missions encompass a wide range of scientific disciplines, from atmospheric science and oceanography to geology, ecology, and climate science, providing comprehensive insights into Earth's processes and phenomena.</p>
        <h3 style="color: rgb(0, 119, 255);">Key Areas of Study:</h3>
        <p>Climate Change: Explore NASA's research on climate change, including the causes, impacts, and potential solutions to global warming and its effects on Earth's ecosystems, weather patterns, and human societies.
            Natural Hazards: Learn about NASA's efforts to monitor and predict natural hazards such as hurricanes, earthquakes, wildfires, and droughts, providing early warning systems and supporting disaster response and mitigation efforts.
            Land and Ocean Dynamics: Discover how NASA's satellites and instruments track changes in Earth's land cover, vegetation, glaciers, and oceans, helping scientists understand the drivers of environmental change and their impacts on ecosystems and biodiversity.
            Air Quality and Pollution: Investigate NASA's research on air quality and pollution, including the sources, transport, and effects of pollutants on human health, ecosystems, and the atmosphere, informing policies to improve air quality and reduce emissions.</p>
        <h4 style="color: rgb(0, 119, 255);">Cutting-Edge Technologies:</h4>
        <p>NASA's Earth Science research relies on a diverse array of cutting-edge technologies, including satellites, instruments, models, and data analysis techniques, to observe, measure, and understand Earth's systems at local, regional, and global scales. From the Landsat series of satellites to the Global Precipitation Measurement (GPM) mission and the Orbiting Carbon Observatory (OCO), NASA's fleet of Earth-observing satellites provides a wealth of data for scientists, policymakers, and the public.</p>
        <h5 style="color: rgb(0, 119, 255);">Applications and Impacts:</h5>
        <!--This is a picture of one of the cutting edge technologies that the space prgram has brought to us such as the satellites-->
        <img src="images/sEoeyvUbZCESaRbMwNXGPi-1200-80.jpg" alt=""width="2000" height="500" style="object-fit: contain;">
        <p>NASA's Earth Science research has real-world applications and impacts, informing decisions in areas such as agriculture, water resources, urban planning, public health, and disaster management. By providing accurate, timely, and actionable information about Earth's environment and climate, NASA's data and research help decision-makers and communities adapt to and mitigate the effects of environmental change.</p>
